<TEXTAREA NAME="ReplyMessage" ROWS=20 COLS=75 WRAP="VIRTUAL">[QUOTE]Originally posted by Huckman:
[I]Totally agree with that point.

If you wanted a game to be multiplayer but it's not- don't make it take the hit in the review score.  If the game was MARKETED as a multiplayer game and is not, then slice it and dice it.

Many casual readers of publications (both print and online) glance over a review score to see if the game is worth their time.  If the review is overtly positive or negative, they will often times dig a little bit deeper.  A review of 3.5/5 says to most people: "It's OK, but not good.  Don't bother unless you have a lot of time/money on your hands". 

CODICIL:  I don't agree with this line of reasoning and think that reviews should be read in their entirety (after all, reviewers are human and humans are inconsistent).  I would LOVE for Larian to make some beaucoup bucks on this game and wish that reviewers would instill confidence to the reader in the SCORE that is often reflected in the TEXT for those shallower readers of the literature.

[/I][/QUOTE]

</TEXTAREA>
